# 2. 本格グループワーク

Saki & Emu: Wow...!
Saki: These are their headquarters...! I'm starting to feel kinda anxious.
Emu: Like it's almost showtime!
Emu: What do you think we're gonna do today? I hope we get to talk to lots of their employees.
Saki: And plan our own event!
Shiho: I get why you two are excited, but you need to settle down a bit.
Shiho: The employee in charge of guiding us is gonna be here soon. You don't wanna cause them trouble, do you?
Employee: There's no need to be so nervous.
Shiho: Oh...
Kizaki: Thank you very much for coming all this way. My name is Kizaki. I'll be your guide today.
Kizaki: I look forward to showing you around today!
Student Leader: Yes, thank you for having us!
Students: Thank you for having us!
Kizaki: Anyway, I'll begin by explaining today's agenda.
Kizaki: First, I'll give you all an overview of what this company does, from our mission statement to our actual business model.
Kizaki: Then, I'll give you a tour of the office. Finally, to cap things off, we'll be asking you all to do a group exercise.
Saki: A group exercise?
Kizaki: Yes, we'll have you sit down and actually plan out an event proposal.
Emu: We get to plan an event? Yay!
Students: What kind of event do you think it's gonna be?
Saki: I'm so excited to find out!
Kizaki: We'll give you the details when we get to the activity, so I hope you'll look forward to it.
Kizaki: Anyway, if there are no further questions, then I'd like to begin explaining what this company does.
Saki & Emu: Thank you!
Kizaki: That concludes the tour of the office. What did you all think?
Saki: Getting to watch real meetings as they took place was so educational!
Emu: I thought everyone was gonna act all super serious, but they seemed to have a lot of fun♪
Shiho: I think what she's trying to say is that things were much more relaxed than we initially expected...
Kizaki: We value having engaging discussions during our meetings. In particular, when presenting new ideas, we try to be as frank as possible with each other.
Kizaki: So, for the groupwork activity, we're hoping that you'll all do the same.
Saki: Understood!
Kizaki: Alright, we'll be holding the activity here, so please break off into groups of three or four.
Emu: Okay! Saki, Shiho, let's form a group!
Saki: Yeah!
Kizaki: Alright, now that you've all found your seats, I'd like to announce the event you'll be working on today...
Kizaki: It will be a product promotion event for a stationery company.
Saki: (A product promotion event... Does that mean it's gonna be like that cosmetics expo?)
Kizaki: I should also mention that this event is based on a real deal we have with our client, Saishi Kobo. They have graciously given us permission to run this activity.
Kizaki: So, please treat the information you hear today with the utmost care.
Emu: Of course!
Kizaki: You will have ninety minutes. Once you've wrapped up your discussions, you'll give presentations to some of our employees. I wish you all the best of luck.
Saki: Wait, we're giving presentations at the end...?!
Shiho: She did say it's based on an actual deal they have with another company. Things just got pretty real.
Emu: Yeah! We'll have to do our best to come up with a wonderhoy event!
Kizaki: Finally, to get your discussions to proceed smoothly...
Kizaki: First, you'll want to read through the documents we've provided on our client, Saishi Kobo. They include the company's mission statement and details regarding a number of their products.
Kizaki: Once you've read those, you should proceed with discussing how you're actually going to promote their products at this event.
Emu: I see...
Kizaki: We'll be walking around to monitor your progress. Please feel free to ask us for help if you get stuck. Your time begins... Now.
Saki: Alright, we're done reading about the company! Let's begin discussing our event!
Emu: Yeah! We're probably supposed to jot down our ideas on this whiteboard, right?
Shiho: Each team gets one, and we've been told to use them however we like.
Saki: Hehe. This is starting to feel like a real planning meeting.
Saki: Let's see. We're supposed to come up with ideas based on Saishi Kobo's mission statement and the key characteristics of their products, right?
Emu: Their mission statement describes what they want to do as a company and stuff, right? In other words, it talks about the things they care about most.
Shiho: Right. At the top of their mission statement, it says, “Helping you send your thoughts”...
Shiho: I guess that means telling others how you feel through message cards and stuff. They've got a number of stationery products for that purpose.
Saki: I see... Which means the event we plan should revolve around the idea of “helping you send your thoughts”, right?
Shiho: Yeah. Also, we have information here saying that the event itself is going to take place in a mall at the beginning of March...
Shiho: It looks like they're going to be releasing a new line of message cards sometime during the month, so this event likely coincides with that.
Emu: Oh, do you think the cards are these ones that were with the printouts?!
Saki: Oh yeah, look! They say “sample” on them!
Saki: Oh, this card is silky smooth! I really like this texture...
Emu: Hehe. I'm tempted to keep rubbing it!
Shiho: Here, it says, “We achieved this delightfully silky texture by using a special pulp mixture.”
Shiho: These cards apparently come in all sorts of colors with different patterns. Check out this page. It has pictures of all of them.
Saki: Wow...! They're all so pretty...!
Shiho: I guess a big lineup will help people find exactly what they're looking for in a message card.
Saki: That makes sense... Oh!
Saki: I have an idea! What if our event involved having people make actual message cards using these?
Shiho: Using these?
Saki: Yeah! By actually using the products, they'll get to experience this amazing texture firsthand...
Saki: And having a huge variety to choose from means getting to have fun deciding what kind of card fits most perfectly for the person they're sending it to.
Shiho: That's not a bad idea. But...
Shiho: Isn't that a little weak, as far as product promotion goes?
Saki: Huh?
Shiho: I used to write letters when I was little, but everyone just messages each other on social media now...
Shiho: I think you're gonna have a hard time convincing people to write out messages by literally putting pen to paper.
Saki: Oh, right... I like writing letters and stuff, but not everyone feels the same way as me...
Shiho: Exactly. So, we need to come up with a way to catch the interest of those people.
Emu: Hmm... What would get them to stop and say, “I wanna make one!”...?
Saki: Hmmmm...
Saki: My head's starting to hurt... I didn't realize planning an event would be this hard.
Saki: There's just so much we have to think about...
Shiho: During the meeting we got to observe earlier, everyone threw out all the ideas they could to make sure their products brought smiles to a wide market.
Shiho: Which means we have to do the same.
Saki: Yeah, you're right...
Emu: Hmmmm...
Emu: Oh...!
Emu: In that case, why don't we think more about the guests we want to attract to our event?
Saki: About the guests...?
Emu: Yeah! The employees said they think about stuff like how old their guests are, what they like, and what they like to do and stuff!
Emu: I think we'll be able to come up with better ideas if we do the same thing and think about the people☆
Shiho: I see... That could make things a lot easier for us.
Shiho: Thanks, Otori. Let's give your idea a try.
Shiho: First, this event's being held at a mall, so it's safe to say that most people will be there to get some shopping done...
Saki: And it's taking place at the beginning of March... What do you think they'll be there to buy?
Emu: Hmm... Rice puffs for the Doll Festival?!
Shiho: That might be too specific.
Saki: (Shopping at a mall... In March...)
Saki: *Gasp*
Saki: I think I know the answer!
